Capstone project: Providing data-driven suggestions for HR¶

Description and deliverables¶

This capstone project is an opportunity for you to analyze a dataset and build predictive models that can provide insights to the Human Resources (HR) department of a large consulting firm.

Upon completion, you will have two artifacts that you would be able to present to future employers. One is a brief one-page summary of this project that you would present to external stakeholders as the data professional in Salifort Motors. The other is a complete code notebook provided here. Please consider your prior course work and select one way to achieve this given project question. Either use a regression model or machine learning model to predict whether or not an employee will leave the company. The exemplar following this actiivty shows both approaches, but you only need to do one.

In your deliverables, you will include the model evaluation (and interpretation if applicable), a data visualization(s) of your choice that is directly related to the question you ask, ethical considerations, and the resources you used to troubleshoot and find answers or solutions.

PACE stages¶

Pace: Plan¶

Consider the questions in your PACE Strategy Document to reflect on the Plan stage.

In this stage, consider the following:

Understand the business scenario and problem¶

The HR department at Salifort Motors wants to take some initiatives to improve employee satisfaction levels at the company. They collected data from employees, but now they dont know what to do with it. They refer to you as a data analytics professional and ask you to provide data-driven suggestions based on your understanding of the data. They have the following question: whats likely to make the employee leave the company?

Your goals in this project are to analyze the data collected by the HR department and to build a model that predicts whether or not an employee will leave the company.

If you can predict employees likely to quit, it might be possible to identify factors that contribute to their leaving. Because it is time-consuming and expensive to find, interview, and hire new employees, increasing employee retention will be beneficial to the company.

Familiarize yourself with the HR dataset¶

The dataset that you'll be using in this lab contains 15,000 rows and 10 columns for the variables listed below.

Note: you don't need to download any data to complete this lab. For more information about the data, refer to its source on Kaggle.

Variable Description
satisfaction_level Employee-reported job satisfaction level [0–1]
last_evaluation Score of employee's last performance review [0–1]
number_project Number of projects employee contributes to
average_monthly_hours Average number of hours employee worked per month
time_spend_company How long the employee has been with the company (years)
Work_accident Whether or not the employee experienced an accident while at work
left Whether or not the employee left the company
promotion_last_5years Whether or not the employee was promoted in the last 5 years
Department The employee's department
salary The employee's salary (U.S. dollars)

Stakeholders:

The HR department for Salifort motors, a fictional alternative energy vehicle company

Task:

Fit an appropriate machine learning model in order to predict whether any employee is likely to leave the company

Initial observations:

Much of the data is categorical, lending itself well to a tree based prediction model. The numerical columns last_evaluation and satisfaction_level are already scaled, while the few remaining numerical columns should be scaled to fit a logistic regression model. There are also some outliers in the time_spend_company (tenure) column that would need to be addressed as part of preprocessing for a logistic regression model. Given this, it would make sense to go with a tree based model.

Resources referenced:

Google and the Google Advanced Data Analytics coursework

Ethical considerations:

The data is anonymized, which is important. Were there individual names for example, they should be dropped from the dataset so that it does not discriminate against employees with similar names. The business plan to address predictive features should be in service of an employee's wellbeing as well as the productivity of the business, so it is important that the data be interpreted correctly.

Variable Relationships:

  • Tenure vs. Left: 3-6 years of tenure have most occurences of left
  • Satisfaction vs. Left: Median is ~ 0.4 for left, and 0.6 for stayed.
  • Avg. Satisfaction vs. Tenure: dip 4-6 years, consistent otherwise
  • Last Eval vs. Left: 0.6-0.8 range has lowest occurences of left
  • Hours vs. Left: 160-220 range has lowest occurences of left
  • Accident vs. employment status: much higher proportion of Stayed had an accident (~3 times that of left)
  • Promotion vs. employment status: much higher proportion of Stayed had promotion (~5 times that of left)
  • Salary vs. employment status: Nearly all High salary employees Stayed (~8% total employees)
  • Department vs. employment status: Mostly uniformly distributed proportion of Left. R&D and Management have relatively fewer employees who Left, while HR has slightly more.

Distributions:

  • Tenure: Median of 3 years, right-skewed distribution. Positive outliers tend to Stay.
  • Satisfaction: Most Left fall below Q1, with a peak at 0.4 and <0.2. Distribution of employees who Stay is relatively consistent across Departments. Sales, Product Management, and Marketing departments have higher values for Q1-Q3 among those who Left. All departments share median satisfaction values within employment status.
  • Department: Sales, Technical, and Support - highest count by a wide margin. Most departments contain <750 employees.
  • Projects: Median of 4, with most employees who Left having 2 project. Most employees with 3 projects Stayed. Total Q1:Q3 is 3:5. All employees at the 95th percentile (7) Left. Left IQR = 1, Right IQR = 4.
  • Last Eval: Most who Left fall outside of total Q1(0.57) and Q3(0.86). Stayed distribution is relatively uniform aside from a big dip below 0.5.
  • Hours: Q1:Q3 = 150:250. Most who Left fall outside that range. No employees who Left fall below 125 hours, while there are a few who stayed with fewer hours. Otherwise similarly shaped distribution to Last Eval.
  • Accident: 15.4% of employees have sustained an accident at work. 84.6% of employees have not.
  • Promoted: 1.7% of employees have been promoted in the past 5 years. 98.3% have not been.
  • Salary: Most employees have either Low or Medium salaries, with less than 1000 of the ~12000 employees having a High salary. The majority of employees have a Low salary, with a relatively small margin over Medium.

Transformations:

Most columns in the dataset were renamed in order to keep them consistent and easier to use. A new column was made for the purpose of more easily plotting titled "employment_status", which represents the boolean values in the "left" column with strings. The categorical columns Salary and Department will need to be encoded in order for a model to interpret them.

Purpose of EDA:

This analysis will help to inform the development of a model to predict whether an employee will leave the company in a few ways. First, by examining the distribution of the different variables, it is made clear whether there are outliers to contend with, and sets expectations for potentially strong predictor variables. EDA also informs us on the types and scale of different variables, which are essential to understand before choosing a model. Model assumptions can also be validated by examining multicollinearity between predictor variables in the case of logistic regression, for example. Structuring and cleaning the data to perform feature engineering begins with the EDA process as well.

Resources:

Google and the Advanced Data Analytics Certificate coursework

Ethical considerations:

Ethical considerations at this stage are largely with respect to the proper interpretation of the data, and ensuring that details are not missed during transformation and analysis that could negatively impact a model down the line. If the proper assumptions are not checked, for example, a model would not perform well on the data. If this goes unnoticed, it could lead to the team making misinformed decisions and wasting valuable resources.

Anything Odd?

The XGBoost model fits the data very well, with all evaluation scores being very high. When tuning the hyperparameters using GridSearchCV, the recall score was prioritized with the "refit" argument. This is to ensure that the model captures as many true positives as possible, even at the expense of precision and accuracy. Despite this, the precision and accuracy scores (and consequently the F1 score) remain high in the final model. It may be the case that the model is overfit. This would become evident as it predicts whether an employee has left on new data.

Independent Variables:

I chose to use all available training features, which required encoding salary and department. This is because an XGBoost model can interpret this unscaled data properly, and does have require that features display no multicollinearity.

Assumptions:

The primary assumption of the XGBoost model in this case is that the data accurately reflects employee behavior.

Model Fit:

  • Accuracy score: 0.985
  • Precision score: 0.985
  • Recall score: 0.924
  • F1 score: 0.953

Improvements:

Feature engineering, the introduction of more data, and comparing the model against other types of models could lead to improvements in model performance.

Resources:

Google Advanced Data Analytics: Course 6 Project Lab

Ethical Considerations:

Since this model was trained and validated on all of the available data, it is essential to compare its performance with incoming data. If the model fit changes drastically, it will need to be retuned and reinterpreted so that the team does not act on poor insights.

Step 3. Model Building, Step 4. Results and Evaluation¶

  • Fit a model that predicts the outcome variable using two or more independent variables
  • Check model assumptions
  • Evaluate the model

Identify the type of prediction task.¶

The prediction task at hand is a classification one, where we will fit a model to predict whether the class of the "left" variable is 0 (Stayed) or 1 (Left).

Identify the types of models most appropriate for this task.¶

Logistic regression, Naive Bayes, Decision Tree, Decision Tree based ensemble models such as Random Forest, or boosting models such as XGBoost are all appropriate for this task.

Key Insights:

  • The model effectively predicted 92.4% of all employees in the test dataset who left the company, while correctly identifying 98.5% of employees who stayed.
  • The following features were most predictive of an employee leaving the company, in order of importance: hours, satisfaction, last evaluation, projects, and tenure.
  • Hours: Among the employees represented in this dataset, those who left very rarely worked in the range of 165-220 average hours per month. This shows that those most likely to leave the company work on average less than 7.5 hours per workday, or more than 10 hours per workday, assuming they work 5 days a week.
  • Satisfaction: Employees with a reported satisfaction level below 0.2 or around 0.4 tend to leave most frequently. Satisfaction tends to be high among those who work 130-260 hours per month on average, with those falling outside of that range tending to have much lower satisfaction levels.
  • Last evaluation: Employees who left rarely had scores in the range of 0.6-0.75, with the distribution of scores outside that range being relatively uniform.
  • Projects:Among the employees represented in this dataset, those who left very rarely contributed to 3 projects. Those who stayed most often contribute to 3 or 4 projects. Average satisfaction is consistently high for employees contributing to a range of 3-5 projects, with the widest distribution of project count belonging to those who left.
  • Tenure: Nearly all employees who left had a tenure of 3-6 years. Most had 3 years tenure.

Business Recommendations:

  • Considering that the number of hours an employee works on average and the number of projects an employee contributes to are strong predictors for this model, initiatives to align employees' workload with those who are less likely to leave would likely be effective in improving retention. Of those who left, most employees worked outside the range of 165-220 hours per month on average. Those who left rarely contributed to just 3 projects, while a 3-5 project workload is most common for employees who stayed.
  • Focusing retention efforts on employees who are approaching 3 years with the company would be prudent, given that most employees who left had a tenure of 3 to 6 years.

Management Recommendations:

  • Employees whose last evaluation score fall in the range 0.6-0.75 tend not to leave the company. Job satisfaction varies much more greatly for employees with evaluation scores in that range who left the company. As last evaluation score approaches 0.8, employees who left tended to have very low satisfaction levels. It could be worth exploring the reasons that those with relatively high evaluation scores are dissatisfied. For example, were these employees previously scoring higher than 0.8 before falling below the threshold that would allow them a raise? We could also explore the ways in which we support those with poor evaluation scores, as they tend to be dissatisfied and leave more frequently.

Model Improvement:

  • The current model performs excellently at predicting whether an employee will leave the company, but will need to be tested with new data and re-evaluated to ensure that the perfomance continues to be strong. Further feature engineering, the addition of more granular data (perhaps the last 3 evaluation scores for an employee, for example), and further hyperparameter tuning could all improve performance down the line.

Questions for the Team:

  • Could we get further data into why employees left the company from exit interviews?
  • Is there more historical data on previous evaluation scores that could be accessed?
  • How is employee workload (number of projects contributed to, average monthly hours worked) determined?

Resources:

  • scikit learn documentation Ethical Considerations:
  • It is important to consider the actions taken when an employee is determined to be likely to leave. We should focus on supporting staff to improve their experience, and should not be punitive to those who are satisfied with more projects despite that being different from the norm, for example. Individuals should be treated with respect and the recognition that they have unique needs and preferences.

Summary of model results¶

In order to train this model, the data was randomly split between training data (75% of the total dataset) and testing data (25% of the total dataset). The data was stratified in order to maintain the same proportional representation of employees who left and employees who stayed within the split datasets, despite being randomly selected.

The model was evaluated using the following metrics:

  • Precision: 0.985
  • Accuracy: 0.985
  • Recall: 0.924
  • F1 Score: 0.953

These scores are all high, representing an excellent overall fit to the data. In this case, the recall score was prioritized when tuning the hyperparameters for the model. The final recall score of 0.924 tells us that the model correctly identified 92.4% of all employees in the test data who left the company.

Conclusion, Recommendations, Next Steps¶

Conclusion:

  • The model effectively predicted 92.4% of all employees in the test dataset who left the company, while correctly identifying 98.5% of employees who stayed.
  • The following features were by far the most predictive of an employee leaving the company, in order of importance:
    • Average number of hours employee worked per month (hours)
    • The employees self-reported satisfaction level [0-1] (satisfaction)
    • Score of employee's last performance review [01] (last_evaluation)
    • Number of projects employee contributes to (projects)
    • How many years the employee has been with the company (tenure)
  • The current model performs excellently at predicting whether an employee will leave the company, but will need to be tested with new data and re-evaluated to ensure that the performance continues to be strong. Further feature engineering, the addition of more granular data (perhaps the last 3 evaluation scores for an employee, for example), and further hyperparameter tuning could all improve performance down the line.

Recommendations:

  • Focus retention efforts on employees who are approaching 3 years with the company, given that most employees who left had a tenure of 3 to 6 years, with newer employees in that range tending to leave more frequently.
  • Establish an initiative to align employees' workload with those who are less likely to leave, where appropriate.
    • Of those who left, most employees worked outside the range of 165-220 hours per month on average.
    • Those who left rarely contributed to just 3 projects, while a 3-5 project workload is most common for employees who stayed.
  • Explore why some employees are dissatisfied despite their performance review scores falling on the high range for those who leave. For example, were these employees previously scoring higher than 0.8 before falling below the threshold that would allow them a raise?
  • Explore the ways in which we support those with poor performance review scores, as they tend to be dissatisfied and leave more frequently.

Next Steps:

  • Continue to validate the model by testing it on new data and evaluating its performance.
  • Improve the model by gathering more data - considering the following questions:
    • Could we get further data into why employees left the company from exit interviews?
    • Is there more historical data on previous evaluation scores that could be accessed?
